text.paragraph:
TEPADINA is indicated to reduce the risk of graft rejection when used in conjunction with high-dose busulfan and cyclophosphamide as a preparative regimen for allogeneic hematopoietic progenitor (stem) cell transplantation (HSCT) for pediatric patients with class 3 beta-thalassemia [see 
                                 Clinical Studies (


                                 14


                                 )
                              ].

Clinically significant hypersensitivity reactions, including anaphylaxis, have occurred following administration of TEPADINA. If anaphylactic or other clinically significant allergic reaction occurs, discontinue treatment with TEPADINA, initiate appropriate therapy, and monitor until signs and symptoms resolve [see 
                                 Contraindications (


                                 4


                                 )
                              , 
                                 Adverse Reactions (


                                 6.1


                                 )
                              ].

Like many alkylating agents, thiotepa has been reported to be carcinogenic when administered to laboratory animals [see 
                                 Nonclinical Toxicity (


                                 13.1


                                 )
                              ]. Carcinogenicity is shown most clearly in studies using mice, but there is some evidence of carcinogenicity in man. There is an increased risk of a secondary malignancy with use of TEPADINA.

